{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505489","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505489"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:31:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:31:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2448"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2448"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.03,0.67,0.03,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2448"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58390"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2448"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2448"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43812"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2877"},{"type":"tags","id":"2900"},{"type":"tags","id":"3854"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1977"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1986"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1999"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18186"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18215"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43154"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58390"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old woman who works as a secretary presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of worsening intermittent joint pain and stiffness, symmetrical in both hands. The stiffness and pain are worse in the morning and improve with use throughout the day. She does not report any swelling or warmth of her joints. She has had no skin rashes of note, other than a few months ago when she had a sunburn on her face that lasted longer than a week. She has also noticed an ulcer in her mouth recently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has no other medical conditions, other than childhood asthma, which she no longer requires salbutamol for. Her mother died at a young age due to \u0027kidney problems\u0027, but all other family members are well. She has a 20 pack-year history of smoking, does not drink any alcohol, and has never used any recreational drugs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most specific in diagnosing the most likely condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anti-nuclear antibody","Anti-smooth muscle antibody","Anti-dsDNA antibody","Anti-cardiolipin antibody","Rheumatoid factor"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient most likely has systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), given her history of intermittent symmetrical polyarthritis, mouth ulcers, and photosensitive skin rash. \u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-dsDNA\u003C/strong\u003E is a highly specific test for SLE, and is the most specific of all of the other options. It is also associated with lupus nephritis, a common and serious complication of SLE that can lead to kidney damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnti-nuclear antibody is the most sensitive test for SLE, but is not the most specific. This means that almost all people with SLE will test positive for anti-nuclear antibodies, but not everyone that tests positive for anti-nuclear antibodies has SLE; largely because other inflammatory conditions can raise anti-nuclear antibodies, such as rheumatoid arthritis, systemic sclerosis/scleroderma, polymyositis, and Sj\u00f6gren\u0027s syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid factor\u003C/strong\u003E is useful in the diagnosis of rheumatoid arthritis, and although this patient\u0027s symptoms may be explained by this, it is not the most likely cause of her symptoms. \u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-cardiolipin antibody\u003C/strong\u003E, in this context, is a test for anti-phospholipid syndrome, which is associated with SLE, but there are no features of this in the stem. \u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-smooth muscle antibody\u003C/strong\u003E is useful in the diagnosis of autoimmune hepatitis and should not be confused with anti-Smith antibody, which is also highly specific for SLE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELupus nephritis is a frequent complication of SLE, and the presence of anti-dsDNA antibodies is often associated with active renal disease in these patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe following is a summary of the relevant antibodies:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EAnti-dsDNA:\u003C/em\u003E Highly specific for SLE, associated with lupus nephritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EAnti-Smith\u003C/em\u003E: Highly specific for SLE, not associated with disease activity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EAnti-smooth muscle antibody:\u003C/em\u003E Useful for diagnosing autoimmune hepatitis, but not SLE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EAnti-nuclear antibody (ANA)\u003C/em\u003E: Highly sensitive but not specific, present in many autoimmune diseases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EAnti-cardiolipin\u003C/em\u003E: Associated with antiphospholipid syndrome, which can occur with SLE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EAnti-Ro and Anti-La:\u003C/em\u003E Associated with Sj\u00f6gren\u0027s syndrome, can occur in SLE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003ERheumatoid factor: Though rheumatoid factor may be present in SLE patients, it is instead far more useful in the diagnosis of rheumatoid arthritis.\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anti-dsDNA is a highly specific antibody test in the diagnosis of Systemic Lupus Erythematosus.","Anti-Smith antibody is also highly specific for Systemic Lupus Erythematosus and should not be confused with anti-smooth muscle antibody.","Anti-dsDNA is associated with lupus nephritis, a common complication of Systemic Lupus Erythematosus."],"references":["Maidhof W, Hilas O. Lupus: an overview of the disease and management options. P T. 2012 Apr;37(4):240-9. PMID: 22593636; PMCID: PMC3351863.","Yung S, Chan TM. Mechanisms of Kidney Injury in Lupus Nephritis - the Role of Anti-dsDNA Antibodies. Front Immunol. 2015 Sep 15;6:475. doi: 10.3389/fimmu.2015.00475. PMID: 26441980; PMCID: PMC4569852.","Justiz Vaillant AA, Goyal A, Varacallo M. Systemic Lupus Erythematosus. [Updated 2023 Aug 4]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK535405/#","van Beers JJBC, Schreurs MWJ. Anti-Sm antibodies in the classification criteria of systemic lupus erythematosus. J Transl Autoimmun. 2022 Apr 13;5:100155. doi: 10.1016/j.jtauto.2022.100155. PMID: 35464346; PMCID: PMC9026971."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43812"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2448"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43812"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-31T15:04:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T17:54:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2448"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58390"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/